<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-ci" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Estimating a confidence interval</title>
    <p>
        In the previous section, we estimated unknown population parameters using sample statistics.
        For example, the sample mean provides a sensible estimate of the population mean.
        However, a single estimate does not tell us how precise that estimate is. Different random
        samples from the same population are unlikely to produce exactly the same sample mean, so
        every estimate contains some uncertainty.
    </p>
    <p>
        A <em>confidence interval</em> provides a way of expressing this uncertainty. Rather than
        reporting only a single estimate, we calculate a range of plausible values that is likely
        to contain the true population parameter. For example, instead of reporting that the mean
        IQ is estimated to be 98.5, we might report that the true population mean is likely to lie
        between 95.2 and 101.8. This interval gives a better indication of the reliability of the
        estimate than the sample mean alone.
    </p>
    <p>
        Confidence intervals are based on the sampling distribution of a statistic. As discussed in
        the previous section, repeated random samples produce different sample means, but these means
        follow a predictable sampling distribution. The Central Limit Theorem tells us that, for
        sufficiently large samples, the sampling distribution of the mean is approximately normal.
        This allows us to calculate confidence intervals using the sample mean, the standard error,
        and a chosen confidence level, such as 95%.
    </p>
    <p>
        A 95% confidence interval for the population mean is commonly written as
        <md>
            \bar{X} \pm 1.96 \times \text{SEM}
        </md>
        where <m>\bar{X}</m> is the sample mean and
        <m>\text{SEM}=\sigma/\sqrt{N}</m> is the standard error of the mean. The value 1.96 is the
        multiplier associated with a 95% confidence level when the sampling distribution is
        approximately normal.
    </p>
    <p>
        In practice, you rarely calculate confidence intervals manually. R-Instat computes them
        automatically for many statistical procedures. The following sections demonstrate how to
        estimate confidence intervals using R-Instat and explain how to interpret the results.
    </p>

    <xi:include href="subsections/estimating_ci/subsec-slight-mistake.ptx" />
